Scientists have found a way to detect kindred stars
Astrophysics from the University of California at Santa Cruz studied turbulent mixing and its influence on chemical homogeneity in star clusters.
It is expected that the opening of specialists will allow you to search among the stars related, that have arisen from the same cluster.
The results of their research, the authors published in the journal Nature, and briefly they can be found on the University website.
Cause the same chemical composition of nearby stars is the turbulent mixing in the clouds of gas that precedes the formation of stars.
Even if born star then leaves the star cluster on its chemical composition to identify the place of her birth, and region of star formation-relatives.
Previously, scientists have little doubt that the evolution of stars outside the cluster may lead to differences in its chemical content from that of relatives in the cluster.
The results of modeling conducted by astronomers show that such differences should not appear.
In their research, experts with the help of a supercomputer has modelled two streams of interstellar gas, which together formed a cloud.
This object for several millions of years under its own gravity converted to the cluster in which they are formed protostar.
Scientists have added paint-markers in the initial gas flows and determined that due to the rapid turbulent mixing in the cloud is achieved a high degree of chemical homogeneity.
