Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis has proposed a bill by which the organization of trade unions is protected as a civil right.
"Where are the unions there and the jobs of the middle class," says Ellison, Democrat from Minnesota, who co-chairs the congressional Progressive Faction.
That is why I am proud to present the Act of empowering employees with the symbol of the civil rights movement by John Lewis.
This groundbreaking bill will give workers the same legal possibilities for discrimination, Union organizing, and other forms of discrimination, stopping the enemy forces of the trade unions
Changing the Law on regulation of labour relations in such a way as to allow employees facing discrimination for participating in the organization of trade unions, to seek justice in the civil courts - and to get damages and penalty payments - reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is certainly not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
Actually, the best way to understand what offer Ellison, Lewis and co-authors of the bill, is to remember a very American idea.
Despite the attacks, which the trade unions have undergone in the last few years in Wisconsin, Michigan and other States across the country - Americans once supported countries all over the world to take, to expand and to respect labour rights.
There was a time that still remember the millions of Americans when this country was simultaneously defending democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after world war II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country to adopt the Constitution, designed to ensure that militarized autocracy Hideki Tojo was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their unions play a role in the formation of a new Japan, they included text, which expressly recognized that "the right of workers to organize, and on the negotiations, and collective action is guaranteed".
When the United States occupied Germany after world war II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans to write a Constitution, which ensured that the fascism of Adolf Hitler has been replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers will need to organize and be heard in the new state, the Germans have included an article that openly stated: "the Right to form associations to protect and improve employment and economic conditions is guaranteed to each person and each profession or field of activity.
Agreements which restrict or seek to restrict this right will not have any legal force; measures aimed at these objectives will be considered illegal.
When former first lady Eleanor Roosevelt was the Chairman of the International Commission on human rights, which amounted to the world Declaration on human rights, in 1948, adopted by the United Nations as a world agreement, Roosevelt and the drafters have included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions for the protection of his interests".
Generations of Americans took for granted the basic proposition that labour rights are human rights.
When this country was advising other countries on how to establish a civil and democratic society, the Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions and to this Union participated as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies - must be protected.
Now, when these rights are under attack in America, wisely, indeed, to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As the Reverend Martin Luther king Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade Union movement has not undermined the strength of the nation, but increased them.
Raising the living standards of millions, unions miraculously created a market for industry and lifted the whole nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack the unions, forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers, as should we.
Official recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of protection of civil rights, to prevent discrimination against the organization of trade unions is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis revive the ideals that have historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
