4 tips on how to achieve the best quality underwater photographs and videos
If you want to take pictures or shoot video underwater, you a number of equipment options.
The cheapest option is a waterproof "soap dish", for example, the Nikon Coolpix AW120, or action camera, for example, GoPro Hero3+ Silver Edition, both of which sold for around $300.
I took these photos on a family holiday with a few cameras, all for about $350.
No matter what equipment you use, a few rules you need to follow in order to achieve the best results.
Recheck your equipment.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure the battery in the camera and the other compartment is tightly closed.
In addition, set up your camera for the type of photos or videos that you shoot.
Some photos and video cameras have scene modes or the type of object that optimize the exposure for dark underwater conditions.
And before you jump in the water, understand how deep your equipment can be lowered.
Some cameras are designed only 5 feet, others 50 or 60 feet.
See our buyer's guide and rankings of digital cameras both for traditional and for waterproof models.
Shoot a few frames - because many of them will not work.
The cameras have a LCD that will help you to compose shots, while action cameras on them usually do not.
Even if you have a LCD, it will be difficult to see under water, and the composition will be a random process.
So do a few frames.
Also, if your camera has a burst mode that takes multiple shots with slightly different exposure settings, use them.
Stay at the surface.
The amount of light is significantly reduced, the deeper you dive under the water.
If possible, stay near the surface, when you shoot in the pool, river or ocean.
It will also allow you to convey more color in photos; the deeper you go, the less color you will see.
Swim up closer to the subjects.
This is a great tip for shooting on land, but it is even more important under water due to dark lighting conditions.
Especially important if you're shooting for action-camera: This instrument often has a fixed, wide angle lens, which means you will have to approach the subject, if you want to fill the frame.
