Anger was the most versatile and functional human emotion
An angry expression is biologically universal to mankind, and everyone involved in its creation, the body and the muscle group is not accidental, but is an additional means of expressing power and threat, researchers found Australia and the USA.
Their findings they reported in the journal Evolution and Human Behavior, and briefly they can be found in the press release of the University of California in Santa Barbara.
Angry facial expression - shifted and lowered his eyebrows, elongated into a thin line of lips, flared nostrils - the same in all cultures, and make it even blind from birth children, who had never seen him, said the study's lead author Aaron sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, the scientists found that experiencing this emotion for the efficient conduct of disputes during the conflict.
The more physical damage one person can inflict on another, the greater the opportunity to dictate terms, and he brings this up to companion with the help of anger.
Researchers have found confirmation and another of his hypothesis: physically strong people often get angry and proceed to assault, feel they have the right to impose disadvantageous conditions for them, and prefer force to solve conflicts peacefully.
Proceeding from the fact that anger is primarily emotion-negotiable", the scientists decided that the movements of each of the seven groups of muscles, creating an angry expression, must submit with the individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interlocutor and thereby force as soon as possible to agree to its terms to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, the researchers modeled on the computer of the person, where was present or absent for each of the seven elements of angry faces, and showed them to informants.
Although drooping eyebrows or chin thrust forward separately did not make the person evil, depicted with such features person stronger physically study participants unanimously acknowledged.
The wrath of man, as in animals, expresses a threat: exaggerated manifestation of our own strength, forcing to accept and obey.
Man inflates his nostrils and pursed lips with the same purpose as that of the frog, which is inflated, or a baboon, which shows its fangs.
"Anger "triggered" rejection of the interlocutor to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form, effectively demonstrating the opposite side of the consequences of this refusal.
